<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="216" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,795,1254]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,795,822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[280,360,796,821]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,360,796,821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from most genera of Moncina by the 
<emphasis box="[1021,1082,796,821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">VHW</emphasis>
with a row of whitish to purple discal spots from Rs to 2A, each one distally limited by conspicuous dark spots. This character is also shared with a few other Moncina species currently placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Godman, 1901" authorityName="Godman" authorityYear="1901" box="[678,937,867,894]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Phanes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[678,760,868,894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Phanes</emphasis>
Godman, 1901
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Godman, 1901" authorityName="Godman" authorityYear="1901" box="[949,1206,867,894]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Artines" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[949,1030,868,894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Artines</emphasis>
Godman, 1901
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1955" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[1219,1436,867,894]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Panca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1219,1291,868,893]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Panca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[1297,1436,867,894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" refId="ref4769" refString="Evans, W. H. (1955) A Catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the Classification and Nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part IV. Hesperiinae and Megathyminae. British Museum, London, 499 pp." type="book" year="1955">Evans, 1955</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1955" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[200,422,903,930]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Vidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[200,269,904,930]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Vidius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[279,422,903,930]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" refId="ref4769" refString="Evans, W. H. (1955) A Catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the Classification and Nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part IV. Hesperiinae and Megathyminae. British Museum, London, 499 pp." type="book" year="1955">Evans, 1955</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[552,632,904,929]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,632,904,929]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from these genera by the male genitalia with the concave ampulla and aedeagus twisted in the median portion, and by the female genitalia with the ductus bursae about as wide as lamella postvaginalis. Additionally, the nudum on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[895,975,976,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[895,975,976,1001]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
antennae bear 11–12 segments, restricted to apiculus; 
<emphasis box="[286,326,1012,1037]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">FW</emphasis>
with a faint vein-like fold from mid cell to origin of M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[930,938,1029,1043]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">3</subScript>
(the recurrent vein of Lindsey)(
<figureCitation box="[1295,1423,1011,1038]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1073,1098]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,175,1054]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,174,1054]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Male forewing showing the recurrent vein (11–12) and brand (13–14) of Tarmia monastica (11, 13) and Tarmia greeneyi sp. nov. (12, 14). The arrows point to the recurrent vein described by Lindsey (1925)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458945/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Figs 11–12</figureCitation>
); male with a sagittate brand on the 
<emphasis box="[532,593,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">DFW</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[607,734,1047,1074]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1073,1098]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,175,1054]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,174,1054]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Male forewing showing the recurrent vein (11–12) and brand (13–14) of Tarmia monastica (11, 13) and Tarmia greeneyi sp. nov. (12, 14). The arrows point to the recurrent vein described by Lindsey (1925)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458945/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Figs 13–14</figureCitation>
) and symmetrical valvae. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[1269,1349,1048,1073]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1269,1349,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Carneiro, Mielke &amp; Casagrande, 2015" authorityName="Carneiro, Mielke &amp; Casagrande" authorityYear="2015" box="[458,1057,1083,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ginungagapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[458,623,1084,1110]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Ginungagapus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Carneiro, E. &amp; Mielke, O. H. H. &amp; Casagrande, M. M." box="[630,1057,1083,1110]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" pagination="196 - 220" refId="ref4701" refString="Carneiro, E., Mielke, O. H. H. &amp; Casagrande, M. M. (2015) The Neotropical genus Ginungagapus gen. nov. (Hesperiidae, Hesperiinae, Moncini): phylogenetic position and taxonomic review. Zootaxa, 3931 (2), 196 - 220. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3931.2.2" type="journal article" year="2015">Carneiro, Mielke &amp; Casagrande, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Carneiro, E. &amp; Mielke, O. H. H. &amp; Casagrande, M. M." box="[1071,1298,1083,1110]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" pagination="196 - 220" refId="ref4701" refString="Carneiro, E., Mielke, O. H. H. &amp; Casagrande, M. M. (2015) The Neotropical genus Ginungagapus gen. nov. (Hesperiidae, Hesperiinae, Moncini): phylogenetic position and taxonomic review. Zootaxa, 3931 (2), 196 - 220. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3931.2.2" type="journal article" year="2015">
Carneiro 
<emphasis box="[1177,1226,1084,1110]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">et al</emphasis>
. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
) in the form of the valva and ampulla. However, the discal spots of the 
<emphasis box="[800,858,1120,1145]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">VFW</emphasis>
, and the other genitalic characters above mentioned are unique to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[346,426,1156,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[346,426,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="216" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,795,1254]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" box="[463,543,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[463,543,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">Tarmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably a reference to the Tarma River, where the 
<typeStatus box="[1163,1211,1192,1218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindsey" authorityYear="1925" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Tarmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monastica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="216">T. monastica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
